I think teaching interactive workshops and live-coding is good practice for organising these events. You learn to think on your feet and not let technical issues throw you off. I used to get very nervous speaking but now I don‚Äôt get stressed running large events.

Projectors will drop slides, mics will get interference, speakers will need to reschedule, the catering will be late, and someone won‚Äôt have a VGA adapter. Give yourself enough time to fix it. People will be more forgiving with finishing early than late.

Today, we're excited to announce the establishment of the Public Health Alliance for Genomic Epidemiology (@PHA4GE). #GrandChallenges2019 #publichealth #openscience #interoperability #bioinformatics #datastandards

I‚Äôm also thankful to organisers and chairs for keeping the sessions on time. The experience of doing this has given me a greater appreciation of the effort that goes into it. We should make sure to thank the organisers when we attend conferences. What they do is very important.

I‚Äôm very thankful to the students for their efforts to present in English. Many did so for the very first time. I hope this was a good experience for them and I certainly learned a lot about the field. The future of research in Japan is in very good hands.

I also feel lucky that I got a lot of opportunities to gain experience presenting during my career education. Many courses, especially in Japan, do not have so many presentations and the inexperience shows in PhD students. However they are very hard-working and talented.

Japanese students often stress over getting perfect accent or grammar but it think it‚Äôs more important to make yourself understood clearly. We are very lucky as English speakers to have others bear the burden of language barrier for science to be an international pursuit.

I will add that all of this is immensely more challenging if you are doing this is a foreign language. Please be considerate of non-native speakers when they present. Especially give them clear questions and time to respond. As answers can‚Äôt be prepared. https://t.co/ZWoAX8tOEC

Canadian election system and US electoral college are basically the same thing; the larger number of seats (i.e. electors in US election) gets to elect the government! (1/4)

In real life the errors from imprecise gearing would probably overwhelm utility, but it's quite an amazing contraption and you can actually pull it around the exhibit.
The exhibit had one other cool object - a modern reconstruction of a "south facing cart", a Chinese invention that uses differential gears to keep a pointer fixed in direction.
So how did other cultures solve these problems?  Those who crossed great deserts?  Or the other seafarers such as in India and China (and probably many more places I'm sadly unaware of)?

The First Peoples of Canada navigated the Arctic zones using snow drift lines -- as the winds are constant enough in direction that these run a reliable direction.  And the sun is always towards the south when you live near the top of the world!
They also used stars as references, with a mental model of the ship as fixed and the islands moving

The exhibit revealed some neat ones from non-Western cultures.  Polynesian islanders used wave interference patterns to intuit islands over the horizon, patterns they recorded in clever diagrams woven of sticks
Vikings had another cool trick - using birefringent calcite to detect the sun when it was over the horizon https://t.co/RAByHsazdV

We still haven‚Äôt figured out the exact biological/evolutionary processes leading to population-specific causal disease effect sizes. But we hope our study improves the understanding of genetic architectures of diseases and complex traits in diverse populations.

We think depletions of trans-ethnic genetic correlation in functionally important regions are likely due to strong GxE, as dominance and GxG are less likely. Our results for skin, immune, and brain genes are suggestive of potential role of positive selection.

In analysis of specifically expressed gene annotations (Finucane et al. 2018 Nat Genet), we find that trans-ethnic genetic correlation is most depleted in skin and immune genes (targets of positive selection), and least depleted in brain genes (targets of negative selection). https://t.co/itISvjayCQ

Accordingly, squared trans-ethnic genetic correlation is also depleted in functional annotations (Finucane et al. 2015 Nat Genet). These include super enhancer, coding, and conserved. https://t.co/VaseHWnssq

We find that squared trans-ethnic genetic correlation is depleted in top quintile of background selection statistic (Gazal et al. 2017 Nat Genet; also see McVicker 2009 Plos Genet). https://t.co/4hD81ncHCx

We developed a new method, S-LDXR, to stratify squared trans-ethnic genetic correlation, and employed a shrinkage estimator to handle noisy heritability estimates. In null simulations, S-LDXR is unbiased. In causal simulation, S-LDXR yields conservative estimates.

In this study, we are interested in answering why trans-ethnic genetic correlation is less than 1 for many diseases and complex traits, which limits trans-ethnic genetic risk prediction accuracy. Our strategy is to stratify trans-ethnic genetic correlation.

How would I make them go away? In general strokes, the application of an earthworm-specific pesticide or biocontrol.Eventually the worms from adjacent properties would invade and there would need to be repeated applications, but it would give the woods a chance to recover.
There's too many earthworms here.They make it difficult for the native woodland plants and easier for invasive plants like Buckthorn to prosper.
I'm reminded of this whenever I look out in our woods or just think about my ongoing restoration project there. Fallen leaves don't last and we have exposed soil for much of the year.
But there has been plenty of time for numerous woodland plant species to have evolved to rely on the thick layer of detritus that develops when earthworms are absent.
Why would I do this? Earthworms are non-native invasive species in Minnesota. They were wiped out by the glaciers and there hasn't been enough time for them to get here on their own.
A subject I idly think about every now and again is how to kill earthworms, without disrupting the soil or the plants growing there.

Another big reason is optimizing a single metric tends to give us tunnel vision which seems to result in becoming evil. See @mathbabedotorg book Weapons of Math Destruction.

There are many reasons but a big one is people seem to undervalue the talent and work it takes to succeed in *their* domain. So being excellent in domain X makes you seem like a genius to your people in domain Y. And vice versa.
This is compared to say just being THE person with the highest grades, with the most money, or even the most relaxed life, and nothing else going for you.
Ex‚ÄîStudy for high grades and compete in sports.
Ex‚ÄîAchieve career success and maintain excellent personal relationships.
Ex‚ÄîCreate a profitable business that is also a great place to work.
This is the goals version of @ScottAdamsSays leveraging multiple skills rather than trying to be the best at one.
Hypothesis: Going for two seemingly opposing goals always results in a better outcome than optimizing for a single goal or metric.

Application to GTEx v8 data is out as a preprint too: https://t.co/rqZL1KZg8Y. Stay tuned for further developments and applications from the @Pejminister lab. Huge congrats and thanks to him for this work - it‚Äôs been so much fun & I‚Äôm really proud of the paper!

With allelic expression, an individual's RNA-seq data can be easily compared to a pop reference (like GTEx), which is analogous to pLI/loueff from gnomAD for prioritization of coding variants. Code & data is available for people to try this on their patients!

By design, ANEVA-DOT doesn't try to pinpoint the variant - we can capture whatever heterozygous variant with an outlier effect on gene dosage. Follow-up with WES/WGS, known rare disease genes, etc, complements this.

Working with @beryl_bbc @dgmacarthur , we applied this to Mendelian muscle disease patients. The median 11 ANEVA-DOT outlier genes included the previously diagnosed gene in 76%, which clearly outperforms other tests. Some new diagnoses too!

ANEVA-DOT allows comparison of one individual's allelic expression data to the population distributions to find the handful of genes where this person has a heterozygous variant effecting gene dosage more than you'd expect in a normal population.

Applying ANEVA to GTEx v7 data allowed us to quantify how much each gene's dosage varies due to genetic regulatory variation in cis. Genes implicated in autism, OMIM dominant genes etc are depleted of variation, probably due to dosage sensitivity.

We developed a new toolkit for allelic expression analysis in populations and individuals: ANEVA (ANalysis of Expression Variation) and ANEVA Dosage Outlier Test (ANEVA-DOT) - both very sophisticated models all built by @Pejminister.

Even though I was part of a department specialising in the genetics of mental health, I still felt I couldn‚Äôt speak about it. I felt I wouldn‚Äôt be taken seriously, so I put off going to my GP for ages. But with encouragement and support from the people I around me, I did it.

Finally, after being put on medication and going through 12 weeks of intensive therapy, I‚Äôm happy to say my symptoms have subsided. This means I can sleep properly, live comfortably by myself, and go about my life without avoiding everything that triggers me.
(The university couldn‚Äôt offer specialised treatment for PTSD, so without private counselling, this was essentially my only option)

A year after it happened, I had a flare-up of symptoms, so I (reluctantly) reached out for help, with help from my academic department and people around me.My GP listened to me and found a study for comparing the effectiveness of treatments for PTSD.

For a great primer of compressed sensing, there's https://t.co/2oLbBJaJ49 . Interestingly there is not as much literature for compressed sensing experimental design, but there is at least this article https://t.co/y7uFIZ6Y2g

Additionally, it turns out that randomly perturbing biological samples is very hard, be it chemically or genetically, there is always some bias and limits of the measurements. Still, I think that the idea of compressed sensing experimental design is fascinating.

So this is great! Our causal signals as sparse and we can randomly perturb with few measurements to recover them. Turns out that many problems in bio are not actually sparse and have hidden complexity (from biological, like complex traits, to technical, like batch effects).

Second, your measurement matrix A has the 'restricted isometry property' which intuitively means that Ax doesn't change the norm of sparse signals x as much, so that they become identifiable. Surprisingly, random measurement matrices of broad classes have this property

There are two things required for compressed sensing to work: first, your signal x is sparse, which we many times assume in bio, explicitly or not, as we think that e.g. only a handful of genes are responsible for a phenotype or only a handful of residues interact/are catalytic

When I first encountered the concept of compressed sensing I was blown away...the fact that you could recover a sparse signal with very few measurements seemed like a game changer to me for bio-related fields where the num of variables is large and the experiments expensive

Thanks to great work from @leland_mcinnes @GCLinderman and others, we have many good options for analysis of highly complex multi-dimensional data. We should consider strengths and weaknesses of our methods, how and why they work. Let's avoid hyperbole and stick to the facts.

Both have distinct advantages over PCA for complex datasets such as single-cell genomics. The results are incredibly useful but we must be careful when interpreting any non-linear projection. It can lead to distortions but we also experience this with almost every world map.

It's inaccurate that tSNE cannot capture global distance or take alternative distance metrics. It is possible to fine-tune either to do that with modern implementations. UMAP is promising to share results with non-experts as it's often easier to interpret structure of variations.

This is a great overview of dimension reduction with UMAP. However, I think the most important difference to tSNE isn't performance (you should be doing #singlecell analysis on a server), it's interpretation. The purpose of doing either is to aid interpretation and share results. https://t.co/7aB0WfWfyS

So for these reasons I think Johnson's plans, while clearly unworkable as they stand, can be tweaked to allow something very practical that respects the GFA, respects the referendum, and respects the will of the people of NI to continue our project of reconciliation. (16/16 END!)
3. Respects the GFA principle that people of NI have the final say, and the authority of Stormont4. We are not shackled inexorably to the EU - we have an exit mechanism. (15/16)

So this, to my mind, achieves a number of the DUP's clear objectives:1. Protects NI's position within the UK (until we decide otherwise)2. Protects (and enhances) all three of our main markets - internal, GB and RoI/EU (14/16)
8. This would not be a "border poll" - a border poll would need to be a separate exercise, but again based on a clear prospectus of the options, as we had with the GFA. (13/16)

6. Any such referendum must contain a clear prospectus of arrangements should we decide to dealign and/or leave the Customs Union7. Such a referendum to be held with a minimum 7-year interval. Simple majority (12/16)
5. In acceptance of point 4 and the Principle of Consent enshrined in the GFA, Stormont will have the ability to legislate to hold a referendum within NI as to whether to stay in or not (11/16)

3. Make it an offence to "not deliver to Northern Ireland" (or charge extra) for GB companies (Listen up, ebay sellers!)4. Accept DUP principle that it is for Northern Ireland to decide whether to remain aligned with the EU Single Market and within the EU Customs Union (10/16)

Here are my suggestions:1. Maintain alignment across all sectors with the EU Single Market standards as the default2. Establish fast-track maximally-facilitated customs checks at the ports and airports to ensure frictionless trade with GB - no tariffs... (9/16)

So can we look at these proposals and see what tweaks would make them work? After all, UK *really* wants a deal with the EU that will maintain the many collaborations (science, security, travel, economy) that have proven so valuable to all of us over the years. (8/16)

The Good Friday Agreement establishes the principle that for changes to the constitutional status of Northern Ireland, it is for the majority of the people to decide, not the local legislature (Stormont, if we can get it running again). (7/16)

However, it does do a number of things:- Gets rid of the backstop- Maintains NI in UK (unless we decide otherwise)- Gives NI control over our relationship with EU- Accepts that social, cultural, economic development across the whole of This Island is vital (6/16)

Critics rightly point out that this will be an administrative nightmare, lead to widespread smuggling, be impossible to police, and severely disrupt internal supply chains in the NI economy. It'll kill inward investment. *As it stands*. (5/16)

The plans have been endorsed by the DUP because they note (correctly) that Northern Ireland's largest external market is GB, rather than RoI or rEU. However the largest market overall is of course our internal (NI) market. (4/16)

Briefly, NI remains aligned with the EU Single Market for sectors of Agri-food & Industrial Goods, with renewal of that ratified every 4 years by Stormont. NI in UK Customs Zone with EU Customs matters handled at company premises or designated clearance zones. (3/16)

I've been giving this some thought in the context of the Good Friday Agreement, and I think there may be some merit in the latest UK Brexit proposals to get rid of the Backstop and preserve NI's constitutional status. (2/16)

Everybody's been trashing Boris Johnson's latest Brexit proposals. However I think they've been too quick to pour cold water. There may be the beginnings of something very positive here for both Remainers and Leavers.I humbly present this thread for your consideration. (1/16)

The idea of such a plant had not occurred to me before tonight when I realized I had genetics that combined into a single plant would result in a very small and short life-cycle dry bean. So, I don't know if this is something that bean researchers have already been working with.

I've heard of miniature varieties of sorghum & millet also used in research, but I'm not finding papers describing them.What I haven't heard about is miniature versions of such important crops as soybeans or common dry beans.

More recently a miniature, short-lived variety of corn/maize was developed. The name? FFMM (Fast Flowering Mini-Maize), or just "Mini-Maize". It grows to less than a meter and can complete five generations in a year, when grown in greenhouse conditions. https://t.co/w39nbCGCQF

University of Florida developed a tomato variety called "Micro-Tom" in 1989. It grows, flowers, & fruits well under six inches tall. There are many papers using the variety, but the earliest I can find describing its use as a model organism is from 2002. https://t.co/Og0AaGZ6AE

Miniature versions of crop are useful for research into the biology of the crop. The small size & short life cycle means that more plants and more generations of plants can be grown in the limited space & time available for their studies.
